reviewText:
Short description:

A surprising underdog!

Pros:
- It is a free game that does not try to extort money from you and it is well made and complete!!! How often do you find one of these?! SERIOUSLY??!?!?!?!
- Combat system feels great and adequate to this game;
- Elaborated dialogues;
- Immersive environments;
- Features a culture rich world (mostly Nordic);
- Memorable characters;
- Fully voiced;
- Re-playability through the different classes your character may assume;
- Challenging.

Cons:
- Graphics may not please all audiences;
- Walking through the map takes a lot of time (although you can speed up the game in the options menu);
- The menus could be a little easier to access (but you can have hot-keys in your keyboard in order);
- The initial quest in the game (where you must gather food) may be a little hard for people not used to this type of game;

Long description:

I must say that this game surprised me.

At first, I was reluctant to play it, because it seemed to resolve around a combat system, and I just wanted a good-old-fashioned point'n click adventure.

However, this game won me in the first few minutes, when the first dialogue came up fully voiced, presenting a memorable character (Thrivaldi, you arr awesome!).

As for my concerns with the combat system, well... I was wrong. The game heavily resolves around pointing and clicking on the environment, and the combat system is actually FUN. It is not rare to find myself wandering the woods, looking for random encounters, so that I can play the combat mini game once more.

The puzzles are challenging and fair. You will feel accomplished by completing them without relying to online sources.

Although not all dialogue lines are interesting, they help to add this sense of immersion to the game.

The game has it's flaws, though...

Walking through the forest may be a pain... Without a warp system, you will spend a lot of time travelling from point A to B, sometimes, only to TRY to gather an item. Repeating this journey will prove to be very time consuming.

The auto save feature is nice; but it would be even nicer if they added a before dying" or "before entering a dangerous area" save
